The paper deals with formal language theory, which is a subfield of theoretical computer science. The use of Kolmogorov complexity suggests that the paper may belong to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also presents new characterizations and methods for regular and context-free languages, which are topics typically studied in the formal languages (cs.FL) sub-category. The paper also uses incompressibility arguments, which are commonly used in computational complexity (cs.CC) and algorithmic information theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. The paper also deals with quantifying nonrecursiveness, which is a topic studied in the logic (cs.LO) sub-category.
